  "prompt": "What is the difference between interim and ad interim order?",
  "response": "In legal contexts, both \"interim\" and \"ad interim\" orders pertain to temporary measures issued by a court, but there are subtle differences in their usage and implications:\n\n1. **Interim Order**:\n   - An **interim order** is a temporary order issued by a court to maintain the status quo or provide temporary relief until a final decision is made in the case.\n   - It is typically granted to prevent irreparable harm or to preserve the rights of the parties involved during the pendency of the case.\n   - Interim orders are usually valid for a specified period or until further orders are passed.\n\n2. **Ad Interim Order**:\n   - An **ad interim order** (Latin for \"in the meantime\") is a specific type of interim order that is issued on an urgent basis, often without a full hearing or detailed consideration of the case.\n   - It is a provisional measure taken immediately to address an urgent situation, pending a more comprehensive review or hearing.\n   - Ad interim orders are often granted ex parte (based on the request of one party without the presence or immediate notice to the other party).\n\n### Key Differences:\n- **Timing**: An ad interim order is issued more urgently, often without detailed deliberation, while an interim order may be granted after some preliminary consideration of the case.\n- **Scope**: An ad interim order is a subset of interim orders, specifically designed for immediate, temporary relief.\n- **Procedure**: Ad interim orders are typically issued ex parte or with minimal notice, whereas interim orders may involve a more formal hearing or notice to both parties.\n\nIn essence, all ad interim orders are interim orders, but not all interim orders are ad interim orders. The choice of term depends on the urgency and procedural context of the case.",
